This class represents a normalization rule - this is a procedure to change the value of a String field.
These rules must be applied in increasing order of their "rule number" field. The rules with the same rule number are applied in an unspecified order.

Defines the order of applying the normalization rules - the greater the rule number is, the later the rule will be applied. Recommended is the usage of non-sequential numbers (for example with 10 increase step) thus allowing to insert easily new rules between the existing ones. It IS POSSIBLE to have two or more rules with the same rule number. The rules with the same rule number are applied in unspecified order.

UML:TaggedValue.UML:TaggedValue.value:
This is a provider-specific command [CIB SRS, 51, 54]
Implements the Load Raw Locations activity: This activity is applicable only on Batches in INITIAL state.
It creates a Location instance with a Target Load Process in INITIAL state for each target location in the source data package. For each Location store its provider-specific code and the date of last change the provider reports. Set the Batch in Ready for Planning state.
If any expected errors are found in this activity, like not connecting to the provider's site, invalid format of the batch, etc. this activity sets the Batch in ERROR state and completes normally.
In a single transaction: 1. Connect the provider's site using the URL from the Batch. If there is a file to download, download it and store its provider-specific URL and its local URL in a Source instance bound to the Batch; 2. In a provider-specific way identify the Locations published, together with their provider-specific code and last modification date. In the case of Best western the name of each subdirectory is the provider-specific code of the target hotel to load, and the creation date of the directory is the last provider change date of the target hotel.
3. Store each such Location bound to the Batch. Assign a Target Load process instance to that Location and set in INITIAL state. 4. Send a Plan Batch Load command.

This is a provider independent command.
This activity is applicable only on Batches in Ready for Planning state.
This activity compares the Locations from the current batch (stored in the database) that are in INITIAL state with the Locations from the last batch loaded from this provider. It identifies the: " new Locations and sets them in TO-BE-LOADED state; " not changed Locations (as of the provider's change date) and sets them to SKIP state " changed Locations (as of the provider's change date) and sets them to TO-BE-LOADED state " missing Locations in the current batch. It adds them to the current batch by copying then from the previous one and sets them to TO-BE-DELETED state. It sets the Batch in Planned state
Note: At this moment the monitoring GUI indicates clearly what actually is going to happen with each of the provided locations (by listing their states).
Goal: sets all Locations in the current batch from INITIAL state to TO-BE-LOADED, SKIP, TO-BE-DELETED state
Processing in a single transaction: Identify the last batch from that provider loaded before the current one
If there is no previous batch: set all Locations in the current Batch to status TO-BE-LOADED else for each Location from the current Batch find the corresponding Location (with the same provider code) from the previous batch and: if there is no corresponding Location from the previous batch or there is one and its provider date is other than the date of the current Location or it is not in SKIP and not in Imported state set the current one to TO-BE-LOADED state
for each Location from the previous Batch which is in Mapped state, find the corresponding Location (with the same provider code) from the current batch and: if there is no corresponding Location from the current batch add the location from the previous batch to the current batch and set it to TO-BE-DEETED state
NOTES: 1. Locations that were meant for import but were not imported should be imported now (these are locations that are not in SKIP and not in Import state) 2. Only mapped to Workbench locations could be deleted
Set the current batch to PLANNED state Send a Dispatch Batch command for the same provider and URL

This is a provider-specific command
Implements the Dispatch Load activity:
This activity is applicable only on Batches in Planned state.
This activity schedules the load of each source file containing target location(s) that are in TO-BE-LOADED state. Note that some providers describe the locations in separate files whereas others use a single file for all locations, so this activity decides which files to load.
It sets the Batch in Loading state. It sets the Source file in Planned state.
In the case when a single location is in a single file (in fact several files in different languages) like Best Western the processing should be:
For each Location in TO BE LOADED state: For each source file representing that location or supplementary data Create a corresponding Source instance bound to the Location and set it to Planned state In the same transaction send a corresponding Receive Locations Fie or Load Supplementary for that Source. Use the Receive Locations File command for source files and use Load Supplementary command for other support files (logos, maps, images, etc.)
Set the Batch to Loading state.
Important: 1. All commands are sent as part of the current transaction. This way, if the transaction fails, nothing is sent. The infrastructure will take care to re-attempt the current command. 2. The other approach - to send the commands out of the current transaction might cause scheduling some locations for load as many times as this command fails; 3. A safe and simple approach might be this command to send an internal command, for example Dispatch Location X Load one for each location in TO BE LOADED state (see the outer loop) as part of this transaction, whereas each separate command will take care for dispatching the load commands for locations X. This way there are no long running transactions and any failure may repeat executing this command or a command for a single location. 4. Use either the JMS queue for sequential of the queue for parallel processing, to send the Commands into.

This is a provider-specific command
Implements the Receive Locations File activity: This activity is protocol-specific This activity is applicable only for Batches in Loading state and Source files in Planned state.
It just downloads the source file from the provider's site, stores it locally and registers its URL and local URL in the database. Leaves the Source file in Received state.
If there are communication problems (the file does not exist, the site is down, etc.) this activity just registers that fact, puts the Source file in Load Failed state and completes normally.
[CIB SRS, 41-46,51, 54]
For the case of Best Western:
In a single transaction: 1. The use an ftp client to connect the (BestWestern) ftp site and download the Source file using the provider URL from the Source instance. 2. Store the file locally and the state of the Source to Received. 3. Send the Change Format command
If any errors like I/O, invalid URL, etc. are reported, set the Source to Load Failed state and commit.

This is a type-specific command
Implements the Load Supplement activity: This activity is provider-specific This activity is applicable only for Source files in Planned state and the Batch is in Loading state.
This activity downloads a single supplementary Source file and leaves it in Loaded or Load Failed state. The downloaded file is stored locally and processed according to specific rules, for example, when downloading maps, their URLs could be additionally stored in the address; when downloading images, they are stored additionally, etc.
It leaves the supplementary Source file into Loaded or Load Failed state.
If all Sources bund to Locations in this batch or bound the batch itself are Loaded state, this activity sets the Batch to Load Completed state and triggers the Validate Batch activity.
For the case of Best Western:
In a single transaction: 1. The use an ftp client to connect the (BestWestern) ftp site and download the Source file using the provider URL from the Source instance. 2. Store the file locally and the state of the Source to Received.
If any errors like I/O, invalid URL, etc. are reported, set the Source to Load Failed state and commit.
It sends CheckBatchLoadStatus command that validates if all Sources bund to any Locations in this batch or bound the batch itself are Loaded state, this activity sets the Batch to Load Completed state and triggers the Validate Batch activity.

This is a provider-specific command.
This command implements the Change Structure/Format activity: This activity is provider-specific. This activity is applicable only for Batches in Loading state and Source files in Received state.
It restructures / reformats the locally stored source file compensating this way known provider problems and differences / deviations from the format. This activity varies from doing nothing, through applying a specific XSLT, to totally changing the format so it becomes one of the already known. If the processing is successful, it changes the local file accordingly, whereas if there are problems found the local file is not changed.
Assumed is a text file output format.
It leaves the file in Format OK state or Format Error state. In case of errors, the activity completes normally and the Content Managers are allowed to change the locally stored source file and re-run this activity.
In the case of Best Western, this command validates the locally stored source file against OTA 2006 XML schema.
If any errors are found this command sets the Source to Format Error state, sets the errors collected as a reason for the state change and commits. When no errors are found this command sets the Format OK state, sends the Convert Char Set command and commits.

This is a provider-specific command
[CIB SRS, 71, 72,73,74,75,81,82,83,92,93]
This command implements the requirements for "Convert Source Data Package to SOURCE data structure" activity:
This is a provider & format-specific activity. This activity is applicable only for Batches in Loading state and Source files in Encoding OK state, only for Locations in TO BE LOADED or LOADED state.
It reads the locally stored source file and converts it to a collection of target locations as structures of domain objects, only for those target locations from the database that are in TO BE LOADED state .
Note that if the source file describes/contains multiple target locations, the locations are processed separately, and any errors in one of them do not fail the processing of the others.
In this conversion it delegates to the actual target location the parsing and normalization of its own representation and its validation in terms of required attributes and relationships to other objects.
If no errors are found, then the target location is stored together with all associated objects and their state is set to Loaded. If there are validation errors found, the target location is not stored, just its corresponding location in the database is set to Invalid state (and the reasons are stored in the corresponding State Change object).
If this activity produced at least one target location correctly (in Loaded state) then it sets the state of the source file to Source Loaded state. Otherwise it sets the source to Content Error state and allows the Content Manager to fix it manually.
If all Sources bund to Locations in this batch or bound the batch itself are Loaded state, this activity sets the Batch to Load Completed state and triggers the Validate Batch activity.
Note that if the Content Managers could push the batch loading to the next step just by setting its state to Load Completed. Then any pending Load activities will just be not applicable any more and will have to complete quickly.
For Best Western:
It reads the locally stored source file, which represents a single hotel in a single language. This command must consider if another command already has stored the hotel details in another language, so this command should be applicable to locations only in LOADED or TO BE LOADED state.
This command reads the hotel details from the locally stored file (for a certain language) and completes it with the details for that hotel already stored in the current Location object. Then it delegates the data normalization and validation to the Location object itself, which actually is provider independent.
If there are no errors found, this command stores the Location (hotel) object and sets it in LOADED state, sets the Source to Loaded state.
It sends CheckBatchLoadStatus command that validates if all Sources bund to any Locations in this batch or bound the batch itself are Loaded state, this activity sets the Batch to Load Completed state and triggers the Validate Batch activity.
This command also stores the Nomenclature Locations bound to the current target location read. This command stores/creates the nomenclature Locations, assigns them an instance of Nomenclature Load Process and sets them to Loaded state.
If errors are found this command sets the Source to Content Error state and sets the errors as a reason for this transition. It does not change the state of the Location. This way the location stays in TO BE LOADED or LOADED state, which allows it to be reloaded after fixing the source file, whereas the errors happened in one language do not affect the correctly stored details in another language, so no data is lost.
[CIB SRS, 83] The data normalization and validation must consider the security best practices in OWASP TOP 10, specifically avoiding cross-site scripting, formatting and active content.

On a pre-defined schedule the Java Scheduler Tool automatically triggers the process' start by sending Trigger Batch Load command. This command triggers the process of batch load for a provider (by code), starting from a provider-specific URL.

This command maps the nomenclature instances from the current batch, that are of class X, which is a mandatory parameter "class name" of this command. Pre-condition:
  • The batch is in Mapping state (the class X is stored in the Process)
This command maps all instances of X NOMENCLATURE LOCATION class within the current batch, that are in Loaded or Waiting for Map state and pertain as NOMENCLATURE to target locations in TO BE LOADED state and produces an output mapping table. If there are NOMENCLATURE locations that are not yet mapped (in Loaded state) or not yet decided on the mapping (in Waiting for Mapping state), this command identifies the candidate Workbench locations of the same class, they can be mapped to and: - if for a nomenclature location there is exactly one matched location from workbench, then: -- it is considered as mapped (with no doubt), -- this command assigns to the nomenclature location the ID of the corresponding workbench location -- sets the location to Mapped state TODO: should surely mapped locations be listed (for review?) int the output file? - if for a nomenclature location there are more than one or just no corresponding workbench locations found, then: -- this location is considered as "waiting for mapping" -- this command lists the nomenclature location in the output file (described with enough details, so that the nomenclature location could be identified when reading that file) and the corresponidng options to map it to workbench locations with their IDs -- sets the nomenclature location to Waiting for Map state This command produces a new Source for the current Batch with: - state Waiting for Mapping - process with whose Process instance stores the class X being mapped, and listing the UNIQUE identified (new or alreday existing) nomenclature locations in Waiting for Map state and all candidates (>1!) from Workbench to map them to. Thus the Source is treated as If there are newly identified nomenclature locations in Mapped state, then start a new parallel execution of the Map Nomenclature command for the NEXT CLASS, i.e. send a new command Map Nomenclature of class . This way if any nomenclature locations can be processed automatically, they just proceed further and the process waits only for unknown locations. If there are NO nomenclature locations of X class identified in Waiting for Map state, this command sends the next mapping command (Map to class X+1). If there is no next X+1 class and there are no nomenclature locations of any class in Wiating for Map statein the Batch, then this command sets the Batch to Mapped state and initiates the Validate activity.

This command indicates that the current parallel (sub)process has completed and ready to be joined with the other subprocess into the super process.
Usage pattern: - the superprocess uses a Dispatch command to spown the subprocesses (commands for parallel execution) and stores their number into the Process instance, by calling subprocessStarted() method for each subprocess command, which actually increases the number of waitng processes. - Store the process instance - whenever a subprocess completes (either successfully or not) it norifies the Process that subprocess completed by calling Process.subprocessCompleted() - the subprocessCompleted() methdo sends this command.
This command just decreaes the number of waitng subprocesses in the Process instance. When that number reaches 0, the supercprocess assumes all subprocesses have completed, so this command sets the process to the next state and issues the next command.
